  "doc_id": "39412",
  "text": "The 3-adrenergic system seems to play a role in opiate tolerance and withdrawal. Acute DAMGO or chronic morphine released [3H]norepinephrine in cortical slices, although there was no additive effect when they were combined [CITATION_1] . Acute morphine produced a depletion of norepinephrine from the hypothalamus (345), forebrain, striatum, or midbrain [CITATION_2] , but that effect developed tolerance with chronic administration. Furthermore, both tolerance to morphine and withdrawal from it produced changes in the 3-adrenergic system, especially in the pyramidal neurons (3). In addition, the symptoms of naloxoneprecipitated withdrawal in morphine-dependent mice were attenuated by administration of the 3-adrenergic antagonists propranolol or atenolol, suggesting they might be effective in the treatment of opiate addiction [CITATION_3] . Clearly, therefore, there is an interaction between the adrenergic and opiate systems.",
